Author: cs50-student#2759
Content: @curiouskiwi can i borrow your attention for moment? am I not understanding something? is the specification wrong? is the file incomplete?

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content:
Hi.  We changed the  source code this year, but it appears that the spec wasn't updated.  I'll make sure it gets fixed.  But essentially,  replace the `search` part with just this:  


This function is called by the typeahead plugin every time the user changes the mashup's text box, as by typing or deleting a character. The value of the text box (i.e., whatever the user has typed in total) is passed to `search` as `query`. And the plugin also passes to `search` two additional arguments, the last of which (`asyncResults`) is a "callback" function that `search` should call as soon as it's done searching for matches. In other words, this passing in of `asyncResults` empowers `search` to be "asynchronous," whereby it will only call `asyncResults` as soon as it's ready, without blocking any of the mashup's other functionality. Accordingly, `search` uses jQuery's `getJSON` method to contact `/search` asynchronously, passing in one parameter, `q`, the value of which is `query`. Once `/search` responds (however many milliseconds or seconds later), `asyncResults` will be called and passed `data`, whose value will be whatever JSON that `/search` has emitted. The plugin can then iterate over the places therein (assuming `/search` found matches) in order to update the plugin's drop-down. Phew.

Author: cs50-student#2759
Content: thank you! i'm still not quite understanding the function asyncResults - where is it defined, or is it something we need to define?

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: it's part of typeahead.js

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: which is one of the scripts in your index.html: https://cdn.rawgit.com/corejavascript/typeahead.js/master/dist/typeahead.jquery.js

Author: cs50-student#2759
Content:
asyncResults isn't anywhere in that file... here's all i can find on asyncResults from https://github.com/corejavascript/typeahead.js/blob/master/doc/jquery_typeahead.md : Datasets can be configured using the following options.

    source – The backing data source for suggestions. Expected to be a function with the signature (query, syncResults, asyncResults). syncResults should be called with suggestions computed synchronously and asyncResults should be called with suggestions computed asynchronously (e.g. suggestions that come for an AJAX request). source can also be a Bloodhound instance. Required.
... is that just saying that we should use that function signature, and if we intend to have asynchronous results (as we do for the pset) we send it to typeahead.js via asyncResults()?

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: you don't have to make any changes to the search function

Content:
But nothing is actually passed to `done` or `fail`. There's no use of them in the code at all. And the begginng of next paragraph sounds like there is:

"Notice that we’re using `getJSON`'s "Promise" interface, per http://api.jquery.com/jquery.getjson/. Rather than pass an anonymous function directly to `getJSON` (to be called upon success), we’re instead "chaining" together calls to `getJSON`, `done` (whose argument, an anonymous function, will be called upon success), and `fail` (whose argument, another anonymous function, will be called upoon failure)."

I don't see any chaining.

Author: NAmbry#2791
Content: when using an FTS table all fields are considered TEXT fields, could that be the problem ? I got it working partially by adding quotes in the request

Author: NAmbry#2791
Content: but it still returns an empty list if the longitude or latitude I compare to is negative

Author: NAmbry#2791
Content: Got it ! So for everyone who will encounter this problem : when you use an FTS table (full-text search), even the latitude and longitude fields will be considered TEXT. You'll have to explicitely CAST those fields to NUMERIC in your request in order to be able to compare their value with < or > (for instance CAST(latitude AS NUMERIC) )

Author: pesce#1361
Content:
hi guys, trying to understand sqlite FTS, 
does the virtual table has any relation with the original table? 
if not can u populate the data from the original to the the virtual ? or do i need to insert the data again to the virtual?

Author: pesce#1361
Content:
so i found u can INSERT selected values from the original table INTO the virtual table, 
so my question now is there a relation between the two tables in such a way that querying one table affect the other?

Author: pranavg189#3530
Content: @pesce  Don't think so. The FTS virtual table is completely separate from the original table. It differs from the normal SQL index in a way that some kind of extra cache/metadata tables are created to make the searching faster.

Author: pesce#1361
Content:
@pranavg189 thanks for answering kinda thought so, 
so say for example that u have dynamic tables where values get added and removed regularly and u want search them, like a blog or something, shouldn't the two tables be modified along the way?

Author: pesce#1361
Content: or is there a better way to use something similar to FTS?

Author: pranavg189#3530
Content: @pesce  By my understanding, yeah, the two tables should be kept in sync somehow in that case.

Author: pranavg189#3530
Content: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19634458/sqlite-regular-table-and-table-for-fts

Author: pranavg189#3530
Content: As per above link, we can use the FTS table to find the corresponding rows in the original table. Hence, it would be better if you only include those columns in the FTS virtual table which need fast searching.

Author: pranavg189#3530
Content: "or is there a better way to use something similar to FTS?" -> As per my testing, the staff solution is using FTS table for the '/search' endpoint

Author: Maarten#1004
Content: What you see there is just URL encoding (both %20 and + translate to a space). If you are unsure what to use, just read up on it and try to judge for yourself I'd say. You can find plenty of discussions on when to use LIKE with wildcards vs using  FTS with CONTAINS/MATCH. Or just try to implement them both and see what works best 😉 .
